{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488822"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:58:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:58:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"552"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/552"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.45,0.15,0.05,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"552"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114600"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/552"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"552"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96603"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3460"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"4208"},{"type":"tags","id":"4493"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"303"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16480"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42098"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44469"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114600"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of worsening right upper quadrant pain. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is localised tenderness in the right subcostal region, while the rest of her abdomen is soft and non-tender. Her white cell count is elevated at 14.2 \u00d7 10^9/L (4.0-11.0) and her liver function tests are within normal limits. An ultrasound examination shows numerous gallstones in a thick-walled gallbladder with surrounding pericholecystic fluid. She is admitted to hospital and started on intravenous fluids and piperacillin with tazobactam.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Laparoscopic cholecystectomy within 24 hours of admission","Laparoscopic cholecystectomy within 72 hours of admission","Elective laparoscopic cholecystectomy in 2-6 weeks\u0027 time","Elective cholecystectomy in six weeks\u0027 time","Immediate percutaneous gallbladder drainage"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute cholecystitis, as evidenced by her right upper quadrant pain, fever, elevated white cell count, and ultrasound findings of gallstones with a thickened gallbladder wall and pericholecystic fluid. The current standard of care for uncomplicated acute cholecystitis is early laparoscopic cholecystectomy during the same admission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic cholecystectomy within 72 hours of admission\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management option. Multiple randomised controlled trials and meta-analyses have shown that early cholecystectomy (within 72 hours) is associated with shorter hospital stays, fewer complications, and no increase in conversion rates to open surgery compared to delayed cholecystectomy. This timeframe allows for adequate resuscitation, antibiotic treatment, and optimization of the patient before surgery while still addressing the acute inflammation before dense adhesions form.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic cholecystectomy within 24 hours of admission\u003C/strong\u003E is also a reasonable approach, but does not offer significant advantages over surgery within 72 hours. Additionally, this very early approach may not allow sufficient time for initial resuscitation and antibiotic effect, and may be logistically challenging in many hospitals where emergency operating room availability is limited.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElective laparoscopic cholecystectomy in 2-6 weeks\u0027 time\u003C/strong\u003E represents a problematic approach. There is a temporal frame, ranging from 1 to 6 weeks after the onset of acute cholecystitis, in which laparoscopic cholecystectomy is not recommended due to an increased risk of serious adverse events.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElective cholecystectomy in six weeks\u0027 time\u003C/strong\u003E is a more appropriate timing for delayed surgery if early cholecystectomy cannot be performed. After 6 weeks, the acute inflammatory process has typically resolved completely, and the adhesions have matured, making them easier to dissect. However, this approach still carries the risk of recurrent symptoms and potential emergency readmissions during the waiting period, which is why early cholecystectomy is preferred when feasible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate percutaneous gallbladder drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is generally reserved for patients who are poor surgical candidates due to severe comorbidities or those with severe sepsis who need source control before they can undergo definitive surgery. This patient is relatively young with no significant comorbidities, making her a suitable candidate for early cholecystectomy rather than temporising drainage procedures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Laparoscopic cholecystectomy within 72 hours of admission is the recommended management for acute cholecystitis.","Early cholecystectomy (within 72 hours) for acute cholecystitis is associated with shorter hospital stays and fewer complications than delayed surgery.","Percutaneous gallbladder drainage is reserved for patients who are poor surgical candidates or have severe sepsis."],"references":["Halpin V. Acute cholecystitis. Clinical Evidence 2014;08:411. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25144428/","Mencarini L, Vestito A, Zagari RM, Montagnani M. The Diagnosis and Treatment of Acute Cholecystitis: A Comprehensive Narrative Review for a Practical Approach. J Clin Med. 2024;13(9):2695. Published 2024 May 3. doi:10.3390/jcm13092695"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96603"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"552"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96603"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T08:32:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T08:32:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"552"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114600"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91